I, personally, think this is one of the best RTS games on Mobile as the controls are fluid, the graphics are good, and the ship and level designs are amazing. My, personal, favorite ship design is the BSE Siege as it feels like an old WWII battleship in the sense that, when upgraded enough, it can crack straight through enemy defenses with ease and take on entire fleets by itself. However, it feels as though the unit selection is a bit lacking due to each of the ships feeling, generally, the same. One why I think this could be resolved is if BugByte added the ability to play has other factions and have access to that faction's tech tree, ships, and weapons. All-in-all I recommend this game to any person who wants a well-rounded RTS experience on mobile.
replyContent: Hi! Well, thank you for such nice words :) Feels nice to read that after our vacation. Very busy with Space Haven but will keep your feedback in mind! Thanks for being with us. And do join our Discord or other channel, like Reddit, to have chat with us!

Thank you for the reply. Understanding the mechanics a little better does help, unfortunately there are still times when luck is against you and can completely ruin a level. There is too much randomness - one time the first enemy spawns can be in the worst places at the worst possible time and the game is lost in the first minutes, then replaying the same level you see almost no resistance until several minutes in. I think there should be stricter parameters so that skill and experience is always the main factor
replyContent: There is a safeguard implemented for the beginning of the game, preventing big warp attacks against the base in the beginning. Other warp-ins come randomly and attack either the player or the enemy 50/50. Note that the capture points are guarded, and not random. The 1 - 3 green marks on them indicate toughness of the guardian warp-in when triggered

Best of its kind so far. Fills a void mobile devices have been lacking. A real time action space strategy game with fully customizable units. Taylor an offensive/defense using research. Difficulty levels for all players. Not complicated. Requires patience as each level is a new game within a larger campaign. It is kept interesting by how difficult it can be at higher difficulties. Lack of story line leads game play into a skirmish style gameplay. Restarting from zero every battle. In my opinion, a comprehensive story line option where progressive gameplay improves a player's balanced start position within each battle, is linear, and story progression occurs based on a previous win/defeat is the only missing component for this game. If this existed I would then call it an RPG. As all of the games mechanics are great, a good "story" mode could be franchised into many different games. Utilizing the potential of the great gameplay, some deeper character profiles with a story the gamer can "role play" with would be icing on the cake.

The previous game (Battlevoid: Harbinger) was so much better. I downloaded this when it was released, hoping it will be 'fixed'. After each mission, you need to research everything from scratch, so it gets VERY TEDIUS & REPETITIVE; life's too short for that! Very bad game design decision, but hopefully their next game will be better.
replyContent: Thanks for the feedback! We will try to improve with coming games :)

In the beginning this game was amazing. Then the flaws began to become noticeable. A feature I figure was intended to drag out gameplay seems to be my biggest reason to stop playing. Everytime you complete a mission offensive or defensive the next mission requires REUNLOCKING everything. So basically you need to waste ample amounts of time to beat the next map. The ai is also heavily buffed forcing you to turtle through quick hit and runs till you get strong enough to flank the enemy or suffer utter defeat. This all in about a 15min-2hr struggle. Seems extremely unrewarding to be punished by forcing us to re-research and unlock tech each end every single map. Hate to say it but skip this game and go back to battlevoid: harbinger, at least you didn't get screwed after every battle and moving to the next map. Also, for battlevoid harbinger, add in the marine cloner. Would be nice to have a feature that shoulda been implemented in the first place.

General: - Too random. Regardless of Threat Level, scenarios range from 1) a carrier and destroyer attack your battlestation before you've had time or resources to do more than build two scythes (tugboats) to 2) you waltze through the sector wondering where the foes are.  - Fog of War seems like a last minute hack. It just blocks your view. Permanent features like capture point locations shouldn't be forgotten when you lose sight. It shouldn't block hpbars of visible ships or reveal hpbars of invisible ships. As far as I can tell it doesn't affect the AI at all. - Starting each mission from scratch makes them somewhat tedious, and combined with the randomness erodes any sense of progress, other than the sector map slowly turning blue.

Boring, grind filled mess. I would love to get my $5 back.   Every mission is the exact same: start with one station, conquer the map.  So once you have played a single mission, you have experienced everything the game has to offer.   And what is on offer, frankly, is a poorly designed mess of an RTS. Unlike many other RTS games (or Harbinger) non of your research or unlocks carry across missions, so you have to repeat everything every mission. Unlocked a weapon last mission? Go ahead and unlock it again. Built a big fleet? Nothing survives, including your custom ship designs.  And everything takes freaking forever to unlock. The top tier weapons take over 10 minutes each to research. Every. Single. Mission. You would need to play dozens of games to earn enough credits to unlock all of the higher tier ships, instead of that coming normally with advancing the campaign, like with any good RTS. That is the kind of "Skinner Box" exploitation that you see in free-to-pay scam games, not a paid game.  The developer, at the start of November 2017, announced they had reduced research times, which is technically true. Since they reduced them by about 10%, when it really needed to be about 1000%, I have no hope that this game will ever be balanced, let alone enjoyable.
replyContent: Hello! Very sorry you felt that way. We did our utmost to create a great game once again. If you are very unhappy you can contact us at support@bugbyte.fi and we can sort this out for you.

Not better than harbinger. Just different. Heres why. U lose the roguelike wonder of drops from enemy ship. You always start each battle with super basic weaponry. Not even missiles. You have to upgrade tech to get it. About 15 mins in. Instead you get a semblance of grand strategy which is a campaign map. Particle effects have been dumbed down probably due to volume, so the oomph of 5 projectile cannons firing in burst mode has been lost. No change in "strategy". There is still no firing arcs. All weapons are mounted on turrets that swivel instantly to where enemy ship is. Means there is no such thing as flanking. Strategy is stacking multiple ships on top of each other (they can occupy the same space) and just as one of ships is about to die, move the full hp ship forward to tank the damage. Wash rinse repeat. Attrition. Not strategy. So separating your ships from battle group is guaranteed suicide. Needs to take a page out of Homeworld 2, where some weapons can only shoot forward, so putting your ships far apart, and flanking, makes much more sense as ships need to turn slowly to aim at you. So its a different game than Harbinger. Not better. I prefered harbinger. 2 hours in this game i got bored.

This game rocks! Well done bugbyte!!! Having to research the same upgrades again and again is a bit tiresome, there should be a way to spend your battlepoints to "lock" some upgrades and have them "pre-researched" on future missions (within the same campaign anyway). "squad" and "select all" buttons are very helpful but wouldn't it be awesome if it also had a "formation" button? Also there is a great staple from harbinger that we all love and greatly miss... BSE Trademark!!! The controls are quite intuitive and easy to manage and the gameplay can suck you in for a good couple of hours at a time, once again, well done!!!!
I loved harbinger and they have improved the game model a good bit here and at 5 bucks it's quite a fair deal, also bugbytes an awesome Dev, can't wait for more ,best wishes.

replyContent:
Hi!

The researched ships should be in the "reinforce" ship units list. It is a scrollable list. Scroll and search for the new unit. It will not be added last, it can be added right in the middle or so.
